I was debugging some performance issues in my game loop. I have a struct like this:
struct Player {
    int id;
    int score; // 8 bytes together?
    float pos; // 4 bytes, ends up in same cache line
};
When I move the score to another memory location it takes forever. What's wrong with this code?

#include <stdio.h>
#include <pthread.h>

void* thread(void* arg) {
    printf("Thread %ld\n", (long)arg);
    return NULL;
}

int main() {
    pthread_t t1, t2;
    pthread_create(&t1, NULL, thread, 1);
    pthread_create(&t2, NULL, thread, 2);
    pthread_join(t1, NULL);
    pthread_join(t2, NULL);
    return 0;
}

This tiny program creates two threads that share the same stack and heap. The kernel call to set up those structures happens internally via a syscall when pthread_create is called.

/* file segfault_test.c */
int main(void) {
    int *p = calloc(1024, sizeof(int));
    for (int i = 0; i < 3000; ++i)
        p[i] = i;
}
What's wrong with it?
